[
    {
    id: "iceberg-endnotes",
    title: "This Wiki Shouldn't Exist: Endnotes, Errata, & Additional Info",
    date: "03/28/2026",
    html: "<p>Hey! If you're here, you probably just watched my video on the <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DOsMFsPItP4\">Michael II Iceberg</a>. If you haven't, this post is going to make absolutely no sense to you, so maybe go do that first.</p><p>Below are the endnotes I referenced throughout the video, plus image credits. Thanks for watching.</p><p>All the best,</p><p>Amy</p><h2>Endnotes</h2><ol><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/1.png\" alt=\"1\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> Okay, quick disclaimer. I'm not distributing this executable. I'm not hosting it anywhere. I'm not making it public. The reason for this should be fairly obvious; I don't know if it's safe. It scanned clean and it behaves normally in a VM, but I'm not a cybersecurity person. I'm not trying to be the dingus who accidentally hosts a vulnerable endpoint because I got excited about an esoteric alt history shoegaze wiki or whatever the hell this is. If this draws attention, the file stays with me. Period. I'm not going to be the Typhoid Mary of malware.</li><br><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/2.png\" alt=\"2\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> Also yes, before you ask: there is a login portal. It's there. It doesn't allow you to create an account. As far as logging in goes, I tried the obvious stuff, the not-so-obvious stuff, the maybe-the-password-is-literally-just-password stuff, and…nada. Nothing. The error messages aren't particularly helpful either. And the fact that the login page exists at all is weird, because who exactly is supposed to log in to a local wiki app that I got as a random attachment? The only reason I can think is, maybe this was actively maintained by multiple users via the internet at some point, and there were varying levels of permissions. But I don't really know.</li><br><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/3.png\" alt=\"3\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> The featured article section on Family Reunion's main page is basically my only fishing rod, and the \"catch\" rate makes no sense at all. Sometimes I refresh like fifty times and something new appears. Other times I can refresh for what feels like an entire season of The Office and it's the same handful of pages cycling endlessly. It's like the application is mocking me or something. I tried to see if there was any pattern, but I can't find one. I even had the thought, \"I could just automate this with Python and scrape it,\" but it doesn't behave like a normal website, and it doesn't seem to expose anything I can grab cleanly. It's like I'm using a vending machine that only dispenses snacks between the hours of 3-4 AM and only if you're standing on one leg with a blindfold on. That kinda thing.</li><br><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/4.png\" alt=\"4\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> So, the thought does occur to me that maybe by illustrating my findings, I'm perhaps kinda like…gamejacking this ARG or something? Or inadvertently co-opting it? If this is someone else's art project, am I stealing their thunder by making my own fan art of their unfiction? I don't know. I'm just telling you where my head's at. That's why the disclosure at the beginning is there, I guess. I just want to make it clear: This is a thing I found. I didn't make it myself. Though I did think maybe some visuals would help get the point across. Otherwise, you'd just be staring at a fairly nondescript wiki application, and that'd get old real quick imo.</li><br><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/5.png\" alt=\"5\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> On the topic of \"Midwest shoegaze,\" I want to make it clear that I did try to research it. And here's the conundrum: you can certainly find people online trying to make \"midwest shoegaze\" into a thing since like the 2010s, probably earlier. But it doesn't line up at all with what this wiki is claiming, which is that it was a distinct scene in the 90s with a defined sound and a whole, like, milieu. You know? If we're using the anthropological definition--shoegaze bands from the Midwest--sure, those certainly existed. But a codified subgenre with a coherent history? That's…not firmly established. Not at all. But please, genre pedants, feel free to correct me.</li><br><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/6.png\" alt=\"6\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> I also tried to reverse image search the various photos in these articles, because that's the most basic verification step one could possibly take in this situation. Problem is, the app doesn't seem to want you to screenshot anything. It straight up does not allow screenshots. Which is…suspicious in its own right. Of course, I figured out a workaround. And it's stupidly simple. I took a screenshot from outside the VM instead of inside it, lol. But even then, Google Images and TinEye gave me nothing. Either these images are truly unique and/or obscure, or the app is messing with them somehow. The other thing is, the main guy doesn't have a clear face shot in any of these articles. He's always looking down at his pedals, which is very on-brand for a shoegaze nerd but not helpful for research purposes.</li><br><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/7.png\" alt=\"7\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> So, there is a dark theme toggle; I just figured I should probably mention it considering I didn't explicitly reference this feature in the video. Yes, I had the exact same thought you're having: \"Oh, it's one of those. Switch it to dark mode and the secrets appear.\" Like, maybe there's some secret text that will be made visible? I'm way ahead of you. I toggled the dark theme on every page I could access and scanned for any notable differences. Nothin. Just…a darker UI, which tbf is easier on the eyes. It's quite literally an accessibility feature. That's it.</li><br><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/8.png\" alt=\"8\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> So, I did actually try to verify the Illinois gubernatorial race stuff. The Libertarian Party of Illinois does maintain records of their candidates, and there's no Randall Shaw listed for any cycle. Then again, this article states that Shaw was in the \"New Libertarian Party,\" so make of that what you will. Maybe it was some kind of offshoot. Political orgs do be infighting. I also checked the Illinois State Board of Elections database. Nothin. The op-ed is even harder to pin down because the wiki specifies that it appeared in the \"Chicago Dawn,\" a newspaper I can't find any record of. Go figure. I searched Tribune and Sun-Times archives just in case and came up empty.</li><br><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/9.png\" alt=\"9\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> Also, can we just acknowledge the obvious? \"Michael II\" is a weird name for a concept album. The wiki frames it as a reference to the archangel Michael, and there is a nod to Paradise Lost in there as well. I'm not exactly a biblical lore autist per se; if that's the direction this is going in, maybe they should've just sent it to that damned \"Wendigoon.\" At the very least, I know that Michael is basically the angel who leads the heavenly army to defeat Lucifer. So \"Michael II\" implies… what, the sequel to that whole conflict? The second coming of a badass commander angel? Sounds like a tired sequel idea. But here's my crackpot theory: it's a reference to the John Travolta movie Michael. And here's why that freaks me out a little: my guitar teacher, Mr. Rosenthal, was obsessed with Michael--in this annoying, ironic way, like he knew it was awful, but he loved it regardless. At times, he would say to me there is often a kernel of the profound in what is by any metric objectively bad art. As an adult, I watched it and, well, it is pretty terrible. Unwatchable. Truly. But the premise and the visuals have this weird charm. So now I've got a mystery wiki about a 90s shoegaze band making a concept album called Michael II, and I'm just supposed to believe that's a coincidence? Maybe it's meant as a sequel to the movie. Maybe that's utterly insane? These two possibilities are not mutually exclusive.</li><br><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/10.png\" alt=\"10\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> On this whole Dole presidency thing: I want to be clear that this isn't just a single throwaway reference. I've counted at least fourteen distinct mentions of a Dole presidency across different articles, and they're internally consistent. The wiki references specific Dole-era policies, economic conditions, and cultural shifts that all seem to logically follow from the premise that he won in 96. The downstream effects of Dole's presidency are quite detailed. Counterfactual type shit. The frozen meal/Lean Cuisine reference in Take It Back tying back to Dole's economic agenda is the kind of detail that makes me think this isn't a mistake or a bit; rather, it is foundational to whatever the hell this thing is. There is some allusion to a \"negative income tax,\" which is not a policy I'm familiar with. But reading up on it, it does seem possible, depending on the implementation, that such a proposal would lead to an increase in the price of certain goods, namely frozen means in this instance. So at the very least, the alt history stuff seems internally consistent.</li><br><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/11.png\" alt=\"11\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> There was a period in my life where I thought if I could just sit with pain long enough, something would change for me. Some kind of breakthrough, I guess? And I don't think that's entirely wrong, but this whole mentality can become its own kind of trap if you're not careful. Suffering starts to become synonymous with being productive, and after a while you're just a person who's really good at being miserable. If I'm being honest, it's actually not that marketable of a skill. The wiki presents Roshan's institutionalization almost as an afterthought, but I think it's possibly the most important detail in her entire article. She built a philosophy around engaging with pain, and apparently it consumed her.</li><br><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/12.png\" alt=\"12\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> The Talk Page contributors have very distinct writing habits, and I've been cataloging them like a weirdo. EchoSis writes in proper sentences with full punctuation and uses semicolons like she's getting paid per semicolon…which tbf semicolons are goated. Those independent clauses are not going to separate themselves. More importantly, she constantly pulls rank as the editorial gatekeeper, though not without good reason as far as I can tell. Usually she does it in response to one of the other dinguses trying to speculate too much about a particular topic. EchoSis is the one keeping this thing on rails. At one point she straight up tells one of the other nerds, \"I'm not approving any edits without sources.\" Her real name appears to be Lydia, based on a post where NewKing82 checks in on her after a particularly intense rant. At one point she admits she wrote something \"after a few too many long island ice teas,\" so my kinda girl basically. NewKing82 almost never capitalizes the beginning of his sentences and tends to drop punctuation at the end. He's the most conversational of the three. Lots of \"lol,\" \"lmao,\" and \"what's the dealio\" type mannerisms. But he'll pivot from cracking jokes to something unexpectedly reflective, like musing about how they all dig into Michael II because \"it's the last place where we can pretend the story still has somewhere unexpected to go.\" HeresTheThing is the chaos agent. I guess we'd call him an \"anti-establishment populist.\" That's like the buzzword nowadays, right? Barely any capitalization, blunt as hell, always pushing some conspiratorial angle…government psyops, chaos magic, occult symbolism, yadda, yadda, yadda. There's a moment where NewKing82 addresses someone named Eric who seems upset about something, and based on context I'm fairly sure Eric is HeresTheThing. The point is, these do not seem to be sock puppet accounts. These are three people with consistent voices, running jokes, and interpersonal dynamics that play out over several years. Which is exactly what makes the abrupt silence after 2005 so…unsettling. Three people invested this much in a project don't just stop all at the same time unless something happened.</li><br><li><img src=\"/img/endnotes/13.png\" alt=\"13\" style=\"display:inline;width:45px;vertical-align:middle;margin-right:8px;\"> I know this is probably not the appropriate place for this endnote, but it does occur to me that if this is a locally hosted application, and the program is somehow able to decrypt the index on the fly, the auth key simply must exist somewhere in the binaries. The program would have to retrieve the auth key at some point, and it's not making any outbound connections. I mean, I've taken measures to ensure this thing doesn't even have access to the internet. So the auth key is here somewhere. It has to be. But I've honestly reached the limits of my knowledge when it comes to encryption and that sort of thing. The real question in my mind is, why encrypt the index when you are storing the auth key somewhere in the same location where the program files exist? It makes no sense. But then I think, well, the maintainers of this software seem intent on preservation and archiving. That seems to be their whole ethos, you know? So, maybe things are obfuscated a bit to prevent any geek off the street from getting full access to the index so that it's at least a little more difficult to tamper with? That's my best guess.</li></ol><br><h2>Image Credits</h2><ul><li class=\"image-credit\">-Sky in Thumbnail: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Sky_over_Munich_02.jpg\">Kritzolina</a></li><li class=\"image-credit\">-UIC's campus: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/26329029@N06/15241244532/\">artistmac</a></li><li class=\"image-credit\">-Pleasure Centre performing in 2022: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shoegaze#/media/File:Pleasure_Centre.jpg\">Issan Sumisu</a></li><li class=\"image-credit\">-Slowdive at the Charlotte (Leicester 1992): <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Slowdive_(12529331344).jpg\">Greg Neate</a></li><li class=\"image-credit\">-My Bloody Valentine @ The Roundhouse: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:My_Bloody_Valentine-16.jpg\">Graham Racher</a></li><li class=\"image-credit\">-Nirvana around 1992: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Nirvana_around_1992_(cropped).jpg\">P.B. Rage</a></li><li class=\"image-credit\">-Eddie Vedder performing with Pearl Jam, Hyde Park, London, July 2022: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Pearl_Jam_(Eddie_Vedder),_BST_Hyde_Park_2022,_London.jpg\">Drew de F Fawkes</a></li><li class=\"image-credit\">-Liam and Noel Gallagher of Oasis, San Diego, September 18, 2005: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Oasis_Liam_and_Noel.jpg\">Will Fresch</a></li><li class=\"image-credit\">-Richey Edwards with Manic Street Preachers in Japan, circa 1991: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Richey_Edwards_(7227817420).jpg\">Masao Nakagami</a></li><li class=\"image-credit\">-Foo Fighters at RDS Arena, Dublin, August 21, 2019: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FoosDublin210819-2_(48620472807)_(cropped).jpg\">Raphael Pour-Hashemi</a></li><li>-Krist Novoselic with Bona Fide Band, Spanish Ballroom, Tacoma, WA: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Krist_Novoselic%27s_Bona_Fide_Band_2024-07-23_-_02.jpg\">Joe Mabel</a></li><li class=\"image-credit\">-Dole with Nancy Reagan, President Reagan, Nancy Kassebaum Baker, and Howard Baker: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://dolearchivecollections.ku.edu/index.php?p=digitallibrary/digitalcontent&id=1231\">Dole Archive Collections</a></li><li class=\"image-credit\">-Robert J. Dole: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/common/image/KS_Dole_Robert_1996.htm\">U.S. Senate</a></li><li>-FDR Portrait: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FDR-1944-Campaign-Portrait_(3x4_retouched,_cropped).jpg\">Gift of Beatrice Perskie Foxman and Dr. Stanley B. Foxman, 2009</a></li><li class=\"image-credit\"-Kelly Clarkson: <a class=\"blog-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Birmingham_O2_Academy_-_All_I_Ever_Wanted_tour_-_Kelly_Clarkson_(4357326385).jpg\">vagueonthehow</a></li></ul>"
  },
  {
    id: "keep-walking",
    title: "Keep Walking",
    date: "01/03/2026",
    html: "<p>It’s the beginning of the year and I already feel like I’m falling behind.</p><p>Work has been not great. Or maybe it’s not objectively bad yet. Maybe it’s just my perception. I don't know. I feel that I’m not performing at the level I used to. For a long time I was basically holding my department together with duct tape and shoe strings, and now I’m noticing things gradually fall into disarray. Usually when that happens, I lock the fuck in and clean up the mess. But lately I just haven't found the energy or motivation. The weirdest part is that no one has noticed. Or worse, they have in fact noticed and they simply don’t care.</p><p>I keep thinking the hammer will drop eventually. Maybe it won’t be dramatic. Maybe it’ll be a polite calendar invite that ruins my week. A fifteen minute call with my manager and HR in which I'm casually discarded like a faulty component in an otherwise smoothly functioning machine.</p><p>And then, because apparently life is a tragi-comic work of absurdism written by someone who despises me, my car is having issues as well. Nothing catastrophic quite yet, just enough to keep me in a low-level state of dread every time I turn the key. I love how cars work: you ignore them for months, and then one day they decide to emotionally blackmail you for $975 (plus the cost to tow it).</p><p>It’s also making me wish, very sincerely, that we lived in a world where cars weren’t necessary. I want to live somewhere truly walkable. Not ‘walkable’ like a real estate listing that boasts about a Subway and Dunkin right down the block near a busy stroad. I mean walkable like I can truly get what I need without piloting a two-ton metal death machine through winter traffic.</p><p>Naturally, games have become a kind of respite for me. And I don't even mean it in the dramatic, ‘I’m escaping reality’ kind of way. It's more more like work is a detour from reality and the games I play at least attempt to convey something real. I can get immersed in a story and let my brain latch onto something that isn’t a circuitous email thread about some inconsequential problem that's apparently become urgent because one of the VPs is having a bad day. I can log off Teams, not have to worry about a supposed emergency in another department suddenly becoming my problem. The danger, obviously, is that retreating into the fantasy of a fictional game world can slowly turn into voluntary isolation if I’m not careful. I’m fully aware of that.</p><p>Still, I am grateful that games can give me a little quiet time. A little sense of direction. Even if it’s fake direction. Even if it’s just ‘go talk to this person, pick up this item, watch this cutscene.’ Rinse, repeat. Sometimes I need something to tell me what to do next, because my actual life feels like thirty browser tabs open and one of them is randomly playing audio and I can’t find which one.</p><p>On a more positive note, I’ve been working on a longer video. It’s going to take a ton of research, and I’m not anywhere close to done. This is the part where it’s mostly notes and scattered ideas and me realizing I need to double-check everything because my memory is not a reliable source. Is this what going down the rabbithole feels like? It’s months away from completion, so I’m trying not to talk about it too much, but it’s been giving me something to focus on.</p><p>I’ve also been trying to keep up with my walks, even though it’s cold now and every part of my body wants to become a multi layered blanket burrito until springtime. I’m aiming for 10k steps a day. It doesn’t always happen, but it helps to have a goal.</p><p>Something weird happened a couple weeks ago on one of those walks. I don’t really want to get into details, mostly because I don’t know what the details even mean, really. Basically, I saw someone on the path who creeped me out in a way that didn’t feel normal. Not ‘oh that person is acting strange’ creepy. More like a sudden feeling of impending doom that made my whole body go on alert, like some ancient part of my brain pressed the big red 'panic' button. It was the way he was dressed that first got my attention, then his weirdly stiff posture. I didn't stick around to ask questions. It's the first time I've just done a complete 180 on that path--turned around and went straight home</p><p>I keep telling myself I’m overreacting. Maybe I am. Maybe it was nothing. But when I got home, I had this impulse to draw the person on a post-it note. I’m not even sure why I did it. I just felt like if I didn’t get it out of my head and onto something physical, it would stay stuck with me.</p><p>Since then, I’ve been avoiding that path. Which is ridiculous, right? It’s a walking trail, not a cursed hallway in a survival horror game. But now I’m at the point where avoiding it feels worse than just going back. Like I’m letting a weird, trivial moment dictate the rules of my life. So I’ve decided I’m going to keep walking that way. I’m going to layer up, put on my headphones, and do the thing I always do.</p><p>Anyway. That’s where I’m at. I’m trying to keep moving, literally and otherwise, without turning into a sad hermit with a disturbingly large Steam library.</p><p>All the best,</p><p>Amy</p>"
  },
  {
    id: "side-quests",
    title: "The Comfort of Side Quests",
    date: "11/16/2025",
    html: "<p>Lately I’ve been noticing an unfortunate pattern in my gaming habits: I am extremely good at getting almost to the end of things, specifically that last stretch where the game gently points at the final boss or the last major quest and says, 'Okay, whenever you’re ready,' and my brain responds, 'Cool, cool. Time to do literally anything else.'</p><p>If you could see my save files lined up next to each other, they’d look like an endless graveyard of 82% completions. I used to chalk this up to simple procrastination, or the vague sadness that comes with finishing something you liked. There’s always that hollow feeling you get after being so invested in a game. Like...what now? I thought I was just avoiding that feeling. More recently, though, I’ve started to wonder if there’s something else going on. Something about the way I relate to endings in general.</p><p>Side quests are easier to justify. They’re the low-stakes part of the experience. Help this villager find their cat. Gather ten herbs. Bring the curmudgeonly old NPC his favorite tea, and maybe he'll say something endearing. None of it is urgent in the grand cosmic sense, but it is soothing. You get a little burst of progress, a little “Quest Complete” notification, and the illusion that your time is being put to good use.</p><p>Conversely, the main storyline has consequences. It changes things. It moves the story forward in ways that are irreversible. You can’t un-trigger the cutscene that makes the town look different forever. Disco Elysium is a good example of this. Once you cross that threshold, the world is altered, and the game starts counting down toward its own quiet disappearance from your daily routine. It reminds me of back in the day when I'd be having a grand ol' time with one of my childhood friends, and it starts getting late. Inevitably, my mom would give me the signal that it's time to call it a night. I used to get so frustrated. So, I think I have problems with finality.</p><p>So naturally I tend to leave things in the middle. This is not exclusive to games or fun nights, unfortunately. I’ve also been doing this with basically everything else in my life. I’ll start reorganizing my apartment and get it to the “chaotic but promising” stage, where all the big stuff is done and what remains is the annoying detail work: the stray cords, the papers that need a real home, the junk drawer that has turned into a junk ecosystem. That’s when I start to lose momentum. The project stagnates at 82% completion.</p><p>The relatively obvious interpretation is that I have some kind of issue with commitment or endings, which, sure, probably. But I don’t think it’s exactly fear of finishing. It’s more that the middle of things is where I feel the most…potential. When a game is still unfinished, there’s always the option of going back to it. When a room is half-redone, it could still become the ideal version I see in my head. When a blog is half-written, it could still turn into something good. There’s a safety in that unfinished middle state. It’s like living in a save file right before the final boss: technically precarious, but psychologically reassuring. You don’t have to face whatever comes after the ending if you never trigger it in the first place.</p><p>The truly annoying thing is that this doesn’t feel like laziness. Not quite. It feels like a coping strategy. My brain genuinely believes it’s being clever: 'If we don’t finish this, then it can’t disappoint you. It can’t be worse than you hoped. It can’t be measured and found wanting.' There’s something almost superstitious about it, like I’m hoarding potential outcomes in a little jar and refusing to open it in case reality doesn’t live up to the imagined version. Meanwhile, the games sit there on my Steam account, quietly judging me.</p><p>This pattern has been especially noticeable with so-called cozy games, which are *supposed* to be low-pressure. No one is yelling at me to min-max my build in a game where the main mechanic is literally feeding ducks. And yet somehow I’ve managed to turn that into another space where I can linger indefinitely at the liminal threshold of completion without ever stepping over that line into terminal finality.</p><p>If this all sounds a little bleak, I promise it’s not. There’s something genuinely nice about having places to inhabit that don’t demand decisive action. But I do wonder what it means when that habit starts to leak into the rest of my life.</p><p>It’s easy to joke about backlog culture, about how we’re all drowning in unfinished games and unread books and half-watched TV shows. But underneath the jokes is a deeper question: what would it look like to actually pick a few things and see them all the way through? Not in a grindy, 'optimize your productivity' sense, but in a gentler, more intentional way. To accept that endings are part of what give experiences their form, even when they’re kind of uncomfortable.</p><p>It’s kind of strange to admit this in a public post, because it makes me sound way more dramatic than I really am on a daily basis. It's not like I’m walking around in a haze of existential crisis all the time. I go to work. I answer emails. I cook dinner. I play my little games about tidying up rooms and petting cats.</p><p>But if your own life currently looks like a collection of half-finished games and half-finished plans, consider this a gentle, non-judgmental nudge: maybe pick one thing and see it through. Just one. You don’t have to speedrun your entire backlog. You don’t have to become the kind of person who always finishes everything. You just have to close the loop on something, if only to remind yourself that you can. Thanks for reading.</p><p>All the best,</p><p>Amy</p>"
  },
  {
    id: "the-meetings",
    title: "Meetings, or, The Endless Performance of Cheerfulness",
    date: "10/26/2025",
    html: "<p>I’ve been thinking a lot lately about why I started this channel in the first place. Partly I guess it’s because I wanted a dedicated space to talk about games and other stuff that makes me feel calm, or at least less like I'm being chewed up and spit out by the machinery. But also, I needed something that felt mine. It's almost kind of nice that no one is really watching my vids. There's less pressure to perform.</p><p>My day job pays the bills, but it’s starting to feel like even the small annoyances are overbearing. There’s a performative aspect to it, a kind of enforced enthusiasm that I can’t always muster. I keep nodding along in meetings while a little voice in the back of my head is saying, 'none of this matters.' Then I go home and play something like Unpacking or Mutazione and remember what it feels like to care about small things again. Just focusing on something else for a bit is grounding in a way.</p><p>I had another one of those endless check-ins today. The kind where everyone talks in circles and you can practically hear the life draining out of the room. It really bothers me when meetings go over time because someone just can't shut up. At some point, I caught myself smiling in that automatic way people do when they’re pretending to listen. My cheeks legit hurt from smiling so much.</p><p>There’s this strange contradiction between how exhausting I find these meetings and how easy it is to forget I'm faking it. Like my face knows the choreography better than I do. My default response before I even get a chance to think. I wonder if that’s what corporate life really is: pretending to be invested in things that truly have no soul. And then the pretending becomes like 90% of the job.</p><p>I’m trying to redirect some of that energy here instead. You know, to make vids that feel like they come from an actual person. I know it sounds dramatic, but sometimes I think making things, even small, personal things, is the only real antidote to being slowly assimilated into work culture via Teams meetings and branded wellness emails. I suspect everyone hates it, but we're all too afraid to speak up.</p><p>So, I guess that’s what this site is for too. A place to put the parts of myself that don’t fit anywhere else. Anyway, thanks for stopping by.</p><p>All the best,</p><p>Amy</p>"
  }
]